    "answer": "",
    "explanation": "This question appears to be a complex one and interviewees often get puzzled by what the interviewer exactly wants. But once you start to analyze possible scenarios, the answer becomes obvious. Let's say that you are the 6th person at the party. Then by generalized Pigeon Hole Principle (Do we even need that for such an intuitive conclusion?), among the remaining 5 people, we conclude that either at least 3 people met you or at least 3 people did not meet you. Now let's explore these two mutually exclusive and collectively exhaustive scenarios: Case 1: Suppose that at least 3 people have met you before. 21\n\nIf two people in this group met each other, you and the pair (3 people) met each other. If no pair among these people met each other, then these people ( 2 3 people) did not meet each other. In either sub-case, the conclusion holds. Case 2: Suppose at least 3 people have not met you before. If two people in this group did not meet each other, you and the pair (3 people) did not meet each other. If all pairs among these people knew each other, then these people ( 2 3 people) met each other. Again, in either sub-case, the conclusion holds. Ants on a square There are 51 ants on a square with side length of 1. If you have a glass with a radius of 1/7, can you put your glass at a position on the square to guarantee that the glass encompasses at least 3 ants?",
