    "answer": "",
    "explanation": "Implied volatility is the volatility that makes the model option price equal to the market option price. Volatility smile describes the relationship between the implied volatility of the options and the strike prices for a given asset. For currency options, implied volatilities tend to be higher for in-the-money and out-of-the-money options than for at-the-money options. For equity, volatility often decreases as the strike price increases (also called volatility skew). The Black-Scholes model assumes that the asset price follows a lognormal distribution with constant volatility. In reality, volatilities are neither constant nor deterministic. In fact, the volatility is a stochastic process itself. Furthermore, there may be jumps in asset prices. B. You have to price a European call option either with a constant volatility 30% or by drawing volatility from a random distribution with a mean of 30%. Which option would be more expensive?",
